body:
Hi! It looks like ternary operator does not expect parameterized class type. Without using `VAL_T` (hardcoded `foo`) it works well.

The code:

```verilog
module test;
  class foo;
  endclass

  class wrapper#(type VAL_T=foo);
    local VAL_T value;

    static function wrapper#(VAL_T) create();
      wrapper#(VAL_T) wrp = new();
      wrp.value = new();
      return wrp;
    endfunction

    virtual function VAL_T unwrap();
      return this.value;
    endfunction : unwrap
  endclass : wrapper

  function automatic foo test(bit sel);
    return sel ? wrapper#(foo)::create().unwrap() : null;
  endfunction

  initial begin
    foo obj = test(1);
    if (obj == null) begin
      $error("obj is null!");
    end
    $finish();
  end
endmodule
```

The error:

```bash
$ verilator --binary test.sv && ./obj_dir/Vtest
%Error: test.sv:20:16: Incompatible types of operands of condition operator: REFDTYPE 'VAL_T' and BASICDTYPE 'logic'
                     : ... note: In instance 'test'
   20 |     return sel ? wrapper#(foo)::create().unwrap() : null;
      |                ^
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
```

Verilator version: Verilator 5.023 devel rev v5.020-171-gba47da658
OS: Ubuntu 22.04.4 LTS
